						<div style="width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#036C9D;"  class="pluginblock" >Writing Concurrent Code with Lock-Free Algorithms with Martin Thompson (CONCURRENT-CODE-01-03)
				</div><table  class="coursedetails">
					<tr>
						<td class="coursedetails"
							style="
							width:47%;
							font-size:small;
							padding:none;
							vertical-align:top;">


							<div style="color:#036C9D;"  class="pluginblockcourse" >CODE: CONCURRENT-CODE-01-03 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; DURATION: 3 DAY/S</div>
							<div class="course_text"><p>Backed by many years of hard-won experience, Martin has created a truly inspiring and challenging course for Java and C++ programmers interested in building low-latency, high-throughput systems.</p>

<p>Taking a unique hardware-up approach, Martin will teach you how to build code that reaches world-class performance levels.</p>
							</div>

							<br />

							<div style="color:#036C9D;"  class="pluginblockcourse" >LEARN HOW TO:</div>

							<div  class="course_text"><ul>
<li>Gain in-depth knowledge of concurrent programming</li>
<li>Develop data structures such as queues, executors, and shared memory IPC transports that significantly out perform any products currently available.
<li>Build high-performance data structures</li>
<li>Understand a new performance testing and profiling discipline that is fundamental to working at the extremes of systems performance.</li></ul></div>

							<div style="color:#036C9D;"  class="pluginblockcourse" >PROGRAMME</div>
							<div class="course_text"><h3>Understanding Mechanical Sympathy</h3>
<ul>
<P><li>Performance considerations on modern hardware</li>
<li>How modern x86-64 hardware informs concurrent and high performance programming techniques</li>
<li>Memory models for software and hardware</li>
<li>Why contention of any type is the enemy and how to avoid it</li>
<li>How we manage contention when we absolutely must</li></ul></P>

<h3>Concurrent and High-performance Algorithm Design</h3>
<ul>
<p><li>Lock-free concurrency primitives<//li>
<li>Signalling state change</li>
<li>Ensuring order</li>
<li>Preventing speculative execution during critical data exchanges</li>
<li>Managing contended state</li>
<li>Wait-free techniques</li>
<li>API design to avoid the latency J-curve</li>
<li>Efficient back-off strategies</li>
<li>Discovering hidden contention and how to avoid it</li></p>


</div>

						</td>

